{"id":"1806.02914","submitter":"Maxim Yattselev","authors":"Christopher D. Sinclair and Maxim L. Yattselev","title":"The reciprocal Mahler ensembles of random polynomials","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Random Matrices Theory Appl., 8(4), 1950012, 38 pp, 2019","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CA math.NT math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider the roots of uniformly chosen complex and real reciprocal\npolynomials of degree $N$ whose Mahler measure is bounded by a constant. After\na change of variables this reduces to a generalization of Ginibre's complex and\nreal ensembles of random matrices where the weight function (on the eigenvalues\nof the matrices) is replaced by the exponentiated equilibrium potential of the\ninterval $[-2,2]$ on the real axis in the complex plane. In the complex (real)\ncase the random roots form a determinantal (Pfaffian) point process, and in\nboth cases the empirical measure on roots converges weakly to the arcsine\ndistribution supported on $[-2,2]$. Outside this region the kernels converge\nwithout scaling, implying among other things that there is a positive expected\nnumber of outliers away from $[-2,2]$. These kernels, as well as the scaling\nlimits for the kernels in the bulk $(-2,2)$ and at the endpoints $\\{-2,2\\}$ are\npresented. These kernels appear to be new, and we compare their behavior with\nrelated kernels which arise from the (non-reciprocal) Mahler measure ensemble\nof random polynomials as well as the classical Sine and Bessel kernels.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 7 Jun 2018 21:39:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-12-02"}
